article.description:
Top-ranked Connecticut rolled to its 62nd
straight victory with a 75-51 win over Syracuse on Wednesday, but
had to do it with leading scorer Diana Taurasi on the bench for
most of the game.

related.description:
Nicole Wolff, a freshman guard for
top-ranked Connecticut, has reinjured her left foot and will be
sidelined for at least three more weeks, coach Geno Auriemma said
Tuesday.

article.headline: Bench production sparks Huskies to victory

images.name: Strother Ann 030212 vert inline
images.caption: Connecticut's Ann Strother, left, looks for a teammate to pass to while Syracuse's Awa Diop applies some pressure Wednesday.

article.linkText: UConn pounds 'Cuse to win 62nd straight game
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) --  No Taurasi. No problem.

<photo1>

	   Top-ranked Connecticut cruised to its 62nd straight victory
Wednesday night with leading scorer Diana Taurasi on the bench.

	   The Huskies had plenty in reserve.

	   Freshman Barbara Turner scored 18 off the bench to lead UConn to
a 75-51 win over Syracuse. Reserve forwards Ashley Battle and
Willnett Crockett combined for 20 points and 20 rebounds, as UConn's post players dominated the much smaller Orangewomen.

	   "I don't think anybody plays harder than Syracuse. They're
really tough kids, but the size difference was too great,'' UConn
coach Geno Auriemma said.

	   The Huskies (23-0, 10-0 Big East) have the longest win streak in
women's collegiate history and are 26 victories shy of tying the
UCLA men's team, which holds the NCAA record for consecutive wins
set from 1971-74. UConn has not lost since the 2001 Final Four.

	   Taurasi was in foul trouble early and picked up her fourth with
15:55 left in the second half and did not return. She was averaging
nearly 18 points, but finished with just five Wednesday.

	   "That's what so great about our bench,'' UConn center Jessica
Moore said. "They're just great sparks for us. We've been in this
situation before. And I thought we did a great job of just stepping
up, taking a deep breath and just keeping our composure.''

	   Moore finished with 15 points and nine rebounds for the Huskies,
who dominated the post and outrebounded Syracuse 57-27.

	   UConn outscored the Orangewomen 32-8 in the paint.

	   "With a team like Connecticut, with the talent that they have,
it's difficult if you get behind to work your way back in,''
Syracuse coach Marianna Freeman said. "I thought we hung as best
as we could considering the team that we had out there.''

	   Julie McBride led Syracuse (8-14, 3-8) with 18 points and had
three of the Orangewomen's eight second-half 3-pointers. Rochelle
Coleman was 4-of-7 from 3-point range in the second half and
finished with 16 for Syracuse.

	   The strong inside game helped the Huskies overcome 33 percent
shooting in the first half. Turner had nine of her points in the
period, scoring easily from the baseline and drawing fouls in the
process.

	   "She's a tough one to guard inside,'' Auriemma said of Turner.
"When she gets the ball anywhere near the basket, I don't think
there's anyone who can stop her.''

	   The Huskies opened with a 9-2 run that featured two inside
baskets from Moore and were never threatened as they built a 35-18
lead at the half.

	   The Orangewomen struggled early from the field, going just
5-of-26 in the first half on 19 percent shooting that included a
seven minute scoring drought.

	   Syracuse center Maja Omanovic injured her left knee in a
scramble for a rebound midway through the second half and did not
return.

	   UConn improved its shooting to 60 percent in the second, largely
on inside baskets from Moore, Crockett and Turner. When the
Syracuse zone defense took away some of UConn's perimeter game, the
Huskies quickly found the open player down low.

	   "As aggressive as they are and as spread out as they were, it
did force our post players to get involved,'' Auriemma said. "And
I'm really happy with the way they responded.''
